<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1122,2011]" box="[151,1388,1122,1147]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">
ANTENNAL CLUB (
<figureCitation box="[355,464,1122,1147]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1767,1789]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,227,1688]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,227,1688]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 6 (a–f). Antennal club of Leptidea amurensis amurensis. a. Antennal club ♂ (x180); b. Antennal club ♀ (x130); c. Distal antennomere (two fused) ♂ (x300); d. Distal antennomere ♀ (x320); e. Central sulcus ♂ (x800); f. Central sulcus ♀ (x800)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3769420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3769420/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Fig. 6a, b</figureCitation>
). The length of the scaleless club is 
<quantity box="[870,956,1122,1147]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.16" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" unit="mm" value="416.0">416 µm</quantity>
in the male and 
<quantity box="[1142,1228,1122,1147]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.2" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" unit="mm" value="620.0">620 µm</quantity>
in the female.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="415" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1122,2011]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">
ANTENNOMERES (
<figureCitation box="[398,465,1158,1183]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1767,1789]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,227,1688]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,227,1688]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 6 (a–f). Antennal club of Leptidea amurensis amurensis. a. Antennal club ♂ (x180); b. Antennal club ♀ (x130); c. Distal antennomere (two fused) ♂ (x300); d. Distal antennomere ♀ (x320); e. Central sulcus ♂ (x800); f. Central sulcus ♀ (x800)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3769420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3769420/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
a–d). Both sexes have five scaleless antennomeres. The distal segment corresponds to two fused antennomeres; the male has a suture on the dorsal surface of the distal antennomere confirming the fusion. The antennomeres are depressed, and the l:w ratio is up to 1: 
<quantity box="[905,952,1230,1255]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.524" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" unit="in" value="6.0">6 in</quantity>
the male and up to 1: 
<quantity box="[1184,1256,1230,1255]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.143" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" unit="in" value="4.5">4.5 in</quantity>
the female. The scaled area covers one antennomere more in the dorsal surface than in the ventral. In the male, the distal antennomere ends in an acute area where there is a small ridge.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1122,2011]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">
SULCI AND PSEUDOSULCI (
<figureCitation box="[497,565,1338,1363]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1767,1789]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,227,1688]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,227,1688]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 6 (a–f). Antennal club of Leptidea amurensis amurensis. a. Antennal club ♂ (x180); b. Antennal club ♀ (x130); c. Distal antennomere (two fused) ♂ (x300); d. Distal antennomere ♀ (x320); e. Central sulcus ♂ (x800); f. Central sulcus ♀ (x800)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3769420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3769420/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
a–f). For both sexes we observed 4 central and 8–9 lateral sulci. In the basal antennomere of the female, there are no sulci or pseudosulci, only a few trichoid and chaetic sensilla scattered; the male basal antennomere have the trisulcate configuration. They are irregular, especially in the male where they appear disaggregated; in the female, they are aggregated. The central sulcus does not occupy the whole length of the antennomere, but approaches the proximal border (
<figureCitation box="[768,879,1482,1507]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1767,1789]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,227,1688]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,227,1688]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 6 (a–f). Antennal club of Leptidea amurensis amurensis. a. Antennal club ♂ (x180); b. Antennal club ♀ (x130); c. Distal antennomere (two fused) ♂ (x300); d. Distal antennomere ♀ (x320); e. Central sulcus ♂ (x800); f. Central sulcus ♀ (x800)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3769420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3769420/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Fig. 6a, b</figureCitation>
); the lateral sulci extend toward the dorsum from the second antennomere. In the male, there are some pseudosulci, whereas in the female they are absent (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1767,1789]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,227,1688]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,227,1688]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 6 (a–f). Antennal club of Leptidea amurensis amurensis. a. Antennal club ♂ (x180); b. Antennal club ♀ (x130); c. Distal antennomere (two fused) ♂ (x300); d. Distal antennomere ♀ (x320); e. Central sulcus ♂ (x800); f. Central sulcus ♀ (x800)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3769420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3769420/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Fig. 6c, d</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1122,2011]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">
MICROTRICHIA (
<figureCitation box="[380,448,1590,1615]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1767,1789]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,227,1688]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,227,1688]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 6 (a–f). Antennal club of Leptidea amurensis amurensis. a. Antennal club ♂ (x180); b. Antennal club ♀ (x130); c. Distal antennomere (two fused) ♂ (x300); d. Distal antennomere ♀ (x320); e. Central sulcus ♂ (x800); f. Central sulcus ♀ (x800)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3769420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3769420/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
g–i). We observed m1, m2, and m4. The st:m1 ratio in the central sulci is 1: 
<quantity box="[1313,1362,1590,1615]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.08" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" unit="in" value="2.0">2 in</quantity>
males and 1:2.5 to 1: 
<quantity box="[305,377,1626,1651]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.398" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" unit="in" value="3.7">3.7 in</quantity>
females.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1122,2011]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">
TRICHOID SENSILLA (
<figureCitation box="[434,518,1662,1687]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1767,1789]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,227,1688]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,227,1688]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 6 (a–f). Antennal club of Leptidea amurensis amurensis. a. Antennal club ♂ (x180); b. Antennal club ♀ (x130); c. Distal antennomere (two fused) ♂ (x300); d. Distal antennomere ♀ (x320); e. Central sulcus ♂ (x800); f. Central sulcus ♀ (x800)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3769420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3769420/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[487,518,1662,1687]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="6.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" unit="g" value="6.0">6g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
). These average ca. 
<quantity box="[745,819,1663,1687]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" unit="mm" value="19.0">19 µm</quantity>
in length. The number of sensilla in the central sulci is 
<quantity box="[151,250,1698,1723]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.366" metricValueMax="9.652" metricValueMin="5.08" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" unit="in" value="29.0" valueMax="38.0" valueMin="20.0">20–38 in</quantity>
the male and 
<quantity box="[407,506,1698,1723]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.874" metricValueMax="11.43" metricValueMin="4.318" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" unit="in" value="31.0" valueMax="45.0" valueMin="17.0">17–45 in</quantity>
the female. The total number is 
<quantity box="[869,941,1698,1723]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.9624" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" unit="in" value="156.0">156 in</quantity>
the male and 
<quantity box="[1097,1169,1698,1723]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3528" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" unit="in" value="132.0">132 in</quantity>
the female.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1122,2011]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">
CHAETIC SENSILLA (
<figureCitation box="[426,511,1734,1759]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1767,1789]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,227,1688]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,227,1688]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 6 (a–f). Antennal club of Leptidea amurensis amurensis. a. Antennal club ♂ (x180); b. Antennal club ♀ (x130); c. Distal antennomere (two fused) ♂ (x300); d. Distal antennomere ♀ (x320); e. Central sulcus ♂ (x800); f. Central sulcus ♀ (x800)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3769420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3769420/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Fig. 6h</figureCitation>
). These average ca. 
<quantity box="[741,815,1735,1759]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" unit="mm" value="31.0">31 µm</quantity>
in length. On each ventral and dorsal surface there are four sensilla, resulting in eight per antennomere. On the dorsal surface the chaetic sensilla are located toward the distal edge of the antennomere. In the basal antennomere of the female, there are up to six sensilla, and in the distal anternnomere up to seven. The longitudinal grooves of the sensilla show small rounded bumps.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1122,2011]" box="[199,1413,1878,1903]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">BASICONIC SENSILLA. Apparently there are no basiconic sensilla in this species, or they are exceedingly rare.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1122,2011]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">
AURICULATE SENSILLA (
<figureCitation box="[473,552,1914,1939]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1767,1789]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,227,1688]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,227,1688]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 6 (a–f). Antennal club of Leptidea amurensis amurensis. a. Antennal club ♂ (x180); b. Antennal club ♀ (x130); c. Distal antennomere (two fused) ♂ (x300); d. Distal antennomere ♀ (x320); e. Central sulcus ♂ (x800); f. Central sulcus ♀ (x800)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3769420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3769420/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Fig. 6i</figureCitation>
). These are 
<quantity box="[691,764,1915,1939]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" unit="mm" value="11.0">11 µm</quantity>
in length. They are scattered in the scaleless antennomere, and occasionally they are in the sulci; they are common on the ventral surface. On the dorsal surface they are scarce, especially in the male, and are located near the lateral sulci.
</paragraph>
